= Part I

#par(first-line-indent: 0pt)[The station clock read 3:03 AM.]

It had been 3:03 for as long as Elena could remember.

Not in the way clocks break, not frozen --- more like it refused to advance the idea of time. The second hand moved. The minute hand twitched occasionally. But the number stayed.

3:03.

The station was empty.

Not empty the way stations are between trains --- empty the way a structure is empty when it has been waiting for exactly one thing to happen. The fluorescent lights buzzed at a frequency just below hearing. The benches were worn smooth. The floor tiles reflected nothing.

She stood at the center of the platform and could not remember arriving.

In the waiting room, a woman sat on one of the benches, wearing a black hat. She did not look up. Her hands were folded in her lap. She could have been sleeping. She could have been waiting. Elena noticed her the way you notice someone in a station at three in the morning --- briefly, completely, without consequence.

She never found out who she was.

#v(0.8cm)
#align(center)[#text(size: 14pt)[\*\ \ \*\ \ \*]]
#v(0.8cm)

Two trains rolled in at the same moment.

Perfectly synchronized, like reflections. They appeared from opposite ends of the same darkness and stopped with a soft mechanical sigh.

Platform A. Platform B.

Both destination boards flickered, then settled:

#align(center)[#smallcaps[Train 7 --- Wyndham]]

She stared at the two boards. The same word. The same train number. Two doors, both open.

She stepped toward the edge of the platform and looked left, then right.

Identical. The same length. The same color. The same interior light, warm and amber, spilling onto the concrete.

There was no announcement. No sign indicating which to board. No reason to choose one over the other.

A janitor passed behind her, broom in hand.

"Which one goes to Wyndham?" she asked.

"They go to the same destination," he said. "Only one will get you there."

He was already gone.

She stood between them for a long time.

#v(0.8cm)
#align(center)[#text(size: 14pt)[\*\ \ \*\ \ \*]]
#v(0.8cm)

Her phone buzzed in her pocket. A message from her mother:

#align(center)[#emph[Whichever path you take, remember what you loved when you were a child.]]

A low sound drifted through the station.

At first she thought it was metal --- some vibration in the tracks. Then it resolved into something else.

A melody.

Thin, distant, slightly warped.

A music box.

Her grandmother's music box.

She hadn't heard it in years. Not since she was seven, sitting on the floor of her grandmother's apartment on a rainy afternoon, turning the little brass key and listening to the melody play while the rain came down outside. Her grandmother in the kitchen. The smell of something baking. The music box on the carpet between her knees, its lid open, the tiny mechanism turning.

One note had always been slightly off. She had loved that. It meant it was real. It meant it was _this_ one and not any other.

It was not coming from Platform A. It was not located anywhere. It was simply... more aligned with that direction. As if the air on that side carried it better. As if the structure itself resonated there and was silent elsewhere.

She closed her eyes.

Platform B: flat. Quiet. Not wrong --- just not connected. Like a hallway that leads to a wall.

Platform A: the melody. Faint, imperfect, real.

She opened her eyes and walked toward it.

The doors of the train on Platform A stood open.

She paused at the threshold.

For a moment, she tried to imagine choosing the other train. Not as a decision --- as an experiment. To test whether the distinction was real.

The idea did not resolve.

It was not wrong. It simply failed to form completely --- like a sentence that begins and then forgets what it was going to say.

She stepped inside.

No one stopped her. No one checked. No one was there to check.

#v(0.8cm)
#align(center)[#text(size: 14pt)[\*\ \ \*\ \ \*]]
#v(0.8cm)

Inside, the train was dimly lit, warm, almost familiar. Not in detail, but in structure --- the spacing of the seats, the curve of the aisle, the way the overhead lights hummed at just the edge of hearing.

She walked down the corridor and sat by the window.

The doors closed behind her. Not with a slam --- with a click. A soft, final sound, like a sentence ending with a period.

The train began to move.

No jolt. No acceleration. Just motion, as if it had always been moving and she had only now noticed.

The station slipped away.

Or perhaps it didn't.

#v(0.8cm)
#align(center)[#text(size: 14pt)[\*\ \ \*\ \ \*]]
#v(0.8cm)

She watched the window.

Outside, there was darkness. Ordinary darkness --- the kind between towns, where the land is flat and there is nothing to reflect the light. Occasionally a road crossing. A signal post. The outline of a building with no lights on.

She leaned her head against the glass.

She had the feeling she had done this before. Not this specific ride --- she could not place a memory. But the shape of it. Sitting by a window, moving through the dark, not knowing what was ahead but knowing it was not behind her.

She thought: _I have been on a train like this._

Not a memory. More like a recognition --- the way your hand finds a light switch in a room you have not been in for years. The body remembers what the mind does not.

She sat back.

Maybe she had chosen differently once. Maybe she had stood on that platform and walked the other way, or not walked at all. She could not say. But something in her --- not thought, not feeling, something below both --- was certain that this was not the first time the choice had been offered.

And that the other times had not led anywhere.

#v(0.8cm)
#align(center)[#text(size: 14pt)[\*\ \ \*\ \ \*]]
#v(0.8cm)

A conductor appeared at the end of the carriage. He moved quietly, his uniform crisp and timeless. He reached her seat and took her ticket. He punched a clean hole in the paper.

"You've taken this ride before," he said.

Elena looked up. "I don't remember."

"You chose differently last time."

"So how do you know this is the right one?"

He handed the ticket back to her. His gaze was steady.

"You returned," he said. "You will not vanish."

He turned and continued down the aisle. His footsteps were silent on the carpet.

#v(0.8cm)
#align(center)[#text(size: 14pt)[\*\ \ \*\ \ \*]]
#v(0.8cm)

The music box was louder now.

Still distant, still thin --- but clearer. One note slightly off, as it always had been. Her grandmother's music box. No other one sounded like that.

She thought about the other train.

What if she had made a mistake? What if the melody meant nothing and she had simply walked toward a sound? She tried again to hold the other option in her mind --- Platform B, the quiet one, the flat one.

It would not stay. Not because it was wrong. Because it had no shape. It was like trying to remember a word you never knew.

This was not a cage. A cage has walls you can see. This was a space in which only one direction was connected, and the others were not directions at all.

She felt something settle.

Not certainty. Not understanding.

Just... alignment.

The train moved through the dark.

Outside, the same flat land, the same unlit buildings, the same road crossings passing one after another.

The melody continued, imperfect and clear.

She did not know if she would arrive. But the motion no longer felt uncertain.

It felt... closed.

#v(1.5cm)

#par(first-line-indent: 0pt)[Somewhere, the station clock still read:]

#align(center)[#text(size: 12pt, weight: "bold")[3:03 AM]]

The platform was empty.

Two trains arrived.

Both marked:

#align(center)[#smallcaps[Train 7 --- Wyndham]]

No one was there to choose.

But the doors opened anyway.

